Analysis of Student Academic Performance

1. Introduction¶

When we talk about student academic performance, having a good teacher or a motivated student is only a small portion of what ultimately contributes to a students success. There are various factors which influence student performance, and we aim at identifying those factors in this project.

1.1 Research Question¶

What are the major factors that influence student academic performance?

2. Methods¶

  • Data Preparation
  • Data Cleaning
  • Exploratory Data Analysis

2.1 Data Preparation¶

  • For this research, we will use 1 dataset downloaded in csv format from kaggle website link here.
  • This dataset consists of the marks secured by the students in 3 subjects: Mathematics, Reading and Writing
  • Its attributes are described below:
Attribute name Descrption
gender Student's gender
race/ethnicity Student's race/ethnicity
parental level of education Education level of parent
lunch Type of lunch each student take
test preparation course Whether student completed test preparation course or not
maths score Student's mathematics score
maths score Student's reading score
maths score Student's writing score

Now let's prepare the data by loading it into python

# create a new column that calculates the average score of each student
student_grades['overall_score'] = round((student_grades['maths_score'] + student_grades['reading_score'] + student_grades['writing_score'])/3,2)

# create a new column that classifies the average score of each student
def classify(score):
    if (score >= 95):return 'O'
    if (score >= 81):return 'A'
    if (score >= 71):return 'B'
    if (score >= 51):return 'C'
    else: return 'F'
student_grades["overall_grade"] = student_grades.apply(lambda x : classify(x["overall_score"]), axis=1)

# change the datatype of the categorical features from string/object to category
for i in student_grades.columns:
    if student_grades[i].dtype == 'object':
        student_grades[i] = pd.Categorical(student_grades[i])      

print(student_grades.dtypes)

Handling Duplicate Values¶

This data contain no missing value, however we noticed 1 duplicate value which will not be removed from the dataset, because we cant say for sure if the row is actually duplicated since each row cannot be uniquely identified by a unique identifier (e.g student id), and it may just be 2 students who have similar features.

2.3.2 Data Visualization¶

Let's visualize how each column is distributed in the data

In [241]:
# plot categorical variables
cat_columns = ['gender', 'race', 'parent_education_level', 'lunch_type', 'test_prep_course', 'overall_grade']
ncols = len(cat_columns)//3
plt.figure(figsize =(25, 35))
for index,col in enumerate(cat_columns):
    plt.subplot(ncols,3,index+1)
    var = student_grades[col]
    
    varValue = var.value_counts()    

    plt.bar(varValue.index, varValue)
    plt.xticks(varValue.index, varValue.index.values,rotation=45)
    plt.ylabel("Frequency")
    #plt.title(col)
    plt.title(col, fontdict={'fontsize': 20})
plt.show()

Grade Distribution by Gender¶

In [237]:
gender = student_grades["gender"].value_counts()
v=student_grades.groupby('gender').maths_score.mean()

# boxplot of grades by gender
plt.figure(figsize =(20, 8))
plt.subplot(1,4,1)
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='maths_score', data=student_grades)
plt.title("Maths score")
plt.subplot(1,4,2)
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='reading_score', data=student_grades)
plt.title("Reading score")
plt.subplot(1,4,3)
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='writing_score', data=student_grades)
plt.title("Writing score")
plt.subplot(1,4,4)
sns.boxplot(x='gender', y='overall_score', data=student_grades)
plt.title("Overall score")
plt.show()

# barplot of grades by gender
student_grades.groupby('gender').agg('mean').plot(kind='barh',figsize=(8,8))
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
plt.title("Student Average scores by Gender")
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize =(10, 4))
pd.crosstab(student_grades.overall_grade, student_grades.gender, normalize="columns").plot(kind="bar")
plt.title("Student Grades by Gender")
plt.show()

<Figure size 720x288 with 0 Axes>

From the above visuals we infer:

  • The Average Math Score of Females is less than that of Males while females has the highest average score in terms of reading, writing, and the final score (average score of the 3 subject).
  • Majority of students received C grade followed by B
  • More female students performed outstandingly than male by earning an "O"
  • More number of boys had a failing grade "F" than female

It is very evident that food and nutriention play a vital role in the growth of a student both, physically and academically. Nutrition plays a key role in the healthy development of the children. Nutritious foods provide the body and mind with the energy needed to grow, feel well, be active, stay healthy and learn. Students are able to learn better when they're well nourished, and eating healthy meals has been linked to higher grades, better memory and alertness, and faster information processing.

Healthy students are better learners.

3. Conclusion¶

This research has shown that male students perform better in mathematics than female students, however female overall performance in mathematics, reading and writing is better than that of male. We also discovered that students from group E ethnicity had the best overall performance. We can't undermine the role of nutritious meals in the academic performance of student, which was evident in our research, as students who had standard lunch were seen to have the best performance. We also noticed that the education level of parents played a vital role in the performance of students. As the education level of parents increases, the overall performance of student also increases. Finally, the benefit of test preparation courses is shown in this research, as students who completed the course had better performance than those who didn't complete it.

In conclusion, we have seen how gender, race, parent education level, eating healthy meal, and test preparation courses play major roles when it comes to academic performance of students.
